@misc{unknown-a,
  title = {The WHO initially declined to label the coronavirus outbreak as a PHEIC, as doing so would be extremely disruptive. The member views concerning this decision were quite divided during the first meeting, but the WHO agreed to reassess this decision in a few days’ time,39 and changed its global risk assessment for SARS-CoV-2 from “moderate” to “high”.83 It maintains that there is no evidence that donors withheld disaster relief funds if a PHEIC was not declared.84 It is worth noting that the WHO repeatedly declined labeling the 2018 Ebola outbreak as such as well, showing that there is a tendency to err to the side of caution.85 When it did in 2019, there was prevailing opinion that the PHEIC designation would be game changing in terms of resources allocated and international response.86 We predict that the PHEIC designation for coronavirus will help mobilize response on a global scale},
  language = {}
}
